<blockquote style="padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px;">
    <p>Perusall is a tool which enables students to collaboratively annotate documents of your choice.
    Students can start a new annotation thread in Perusall by simply posting a question or comment to a selected piece of text or image, 
    which other students can reply to or upvote.<br><br>
    Only the &nbsp;<i class="icon-quiz"></i> quick start has to be completed to set up Perusall for your course. 
    If you need help or advice, don't hesitate to <a href="https://outlook.office365.com/owa/calendar/ICTOSocialSciences@Amsuni.onmicrosoft.com/bookings/" target="_blank">book an appointment</a> with ICTO!</p>
</blockquote>
<br><h3><i class="icon-quiz"></i> <span style="font-size: 18pt; color: #34495e;"><strong>Quick start</strong></span></h3>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ1" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>1. Create a Perusall assignment in Canvas</a></span></span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ1" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p><b>Please do not skip any of the steps below. If you do, your Perusall set up might not function.</b></p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to the Assignments page in your Canvas course.</li>
                    <li>Click on <u>+ Assignment</u>.</li>
                    <li>Fill in <u>10</u> points as the maximum number of points.</li>
                    <li>Select <u>External tool</u> as the submission type.</li>
                    <li>Select <u>Perusall</u> from the list of external tools.</li>
                    <li>Select <u>Load this tool in a new tab</u>. Your submission type should now be set up like in the image below.
                        <img src="/courses/8175/files/8525497/preview" alt="submission_type_perusall" /></li>
                    <li>Assign the assignment to everyone, fill in a due date and click <u>Save</u>.</li>
                </ol>
                <p>You've created a Canvas assignment for Perusall! The next step is to go to Perusall, add a document and create an assignment in there.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ2" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>2. Add assignments and documents to Perusall</a></span> </span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ2" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
            <ol>
                <li>Before you can create an assignment in Perusall, you'll have to upload the documents which students have to annotate to your Perusall library.</li>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to the Perusall assignment you've just created in Canvas.</li>
                    <li>Click on <u>Load [assignment name here] in a new window</u> to open Perusall.</li>
                    <li>Go to the <u>Library</u> tab and click <u>+ Add content</u>.</li>
                    <li>Select how you want to upload your document. You can upload documents from your own computer by clicking on <u>Documents from my device</u>, but feel free to try out the other options!
                        <img src="/courses/8175/files/8526428/preview" alt="add_content" /></li>
                    <li>Select the document you wish to upload to Perusall.</li><br>
                </ol>
                
                <li>You've added your document to Perusall! The next step is to create an assignment to which the document is attached.</li>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to the <u>Assignments</u> tab.</li>
                    <li>Click on <u>+ Add assignment</u>.
                        <img src="/courses/8175/files/8526889/preview" alt="add_assignment_perusall" /></li>
                    <li>Select the document you wish to couple to this assignment. You can add as many documents to an assignment as you wish.</li>
                    <li>Click on <u>Next step</u> to go the options tab.</li>
                    <li>Set your submission deadline to the <u>same deadline</u> as in Canvas. If these do not match, you will not be able to automatically export your grades to Canvas!</li>
                    <li>Fill in the <u>exact same assignment name</u> as in Canvas. Again, if these do not match, you will not be able to automatically export your grades to Canvas!
                        <img src="/courses/8175/files/8527270/preview" alt="assignment_name_and_date" /></li>
                    <li>Customize the other settings to your liking and click on <u>OK</u> to create the assignment.</li>
                </ol>
            </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ3" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>3. Create groups within Perusall</a></span></span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ3" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p>If all students were to annotate one and the same document in Perusall, it'd quickly turn unreadable because of all the yellow highlights. To prevent this, Perusall has a grouping feature which distributes students across groups. Students can only see the annotations of their fellow group members.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to the <u>Settings</u> menu in Perusall.</li>
                    <li>Go to the <u>Grouping</u> tab.
                        <img src="/courses/8175/files/8528236/preview" alt="grouping" /></li>
                    <li>You can choose to either let Perusall <u>distribute students randomly</u> or <u>specify groups</u> yourself. 
                        <br><b>a) Distribute students randomly:</b> Simply fill in the number of students in your course and the desired group size. <u><b>Note:</b></u> Perusall will create new group distributions for every single document when using the automatic group distribution feature. If you want students to stay in the same group throughout the course, you must specify the groups yourself. 
                        <br><b>b) Specify groups:</b> Simply fill in a group number in front of the student name to assign a student to that group. <u><b>Note:</b></u> You will not see any students, until they have opened Perusall. You can only manually assign students to a group once they've openend Perusall. It's advised to have students open Perusall at least once before they can access the assignments, so that you can distribute them across groups beforehand.</li>
                    <li>Click <u>Save changes</u> to save the group settings.</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ4" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>4. Configure the grade calculation</a></span></span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ4" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p>Perusall has an automatic grading feature, which can be used configured on multiple criteria: annotation quality, opening of the assignment, reading to the end of the assignment, active engagement time, receiving responses, upvoting and quizzes. determines whether a comment is high, medium or low quality, solely based on the comment's content.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to the <u>Settings</u> in Perusall.</li>
                    <li>Select your desired annotation language.</li>
                    <li>Click <u>Save changes</u> at the bottom of the page.</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ5" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>5. Select the correct annotation language</a></span></span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ5" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p>Perusall's automatic grading supports both Dutch and English, so it's important to select the correct one before your course starts.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to the <u>Settings</u> in Perusall.</li>
                    <li>Select your desired annotation language.</li>
                    <li>Click <u>Save changes</u> at the bottom of the page.</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>

<br><h3><i class="icon-standards"></i> <span style="font-size: 18pt; color: #34495e;"><strong>Copyright</strong></span></h3>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ9" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>What documents am I allowed to use in Perusall?</a></span> </span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ9" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p>You can check for potential copyright issues when uploading the reading material using this <a href="https://h5p.org/node/570927" target="_blank">Dutch</a> or <a href="https://tinyurl.com/45ej8dj2" target="_blank">English</a> decision tree.
                Please note that it's always permitted to use 25% (or less) of a book or journal issue up to a maximum of 50 pages, due to an exception for educational institutions. 
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
<br><h3><i class="icon-stats"></i> <span style="font-size: 18pt; color: #34495e;"><strong>Analysis</strong></span></h3>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ6" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>Can I get an overview of the most upvoted annotations to use in my lectures?</a></span> </span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ6" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p>It is important to ask yourself whether you would like students to enter any comments they might have in TestVision. It is also possible for you to discuss any questions or comments with students on the spot. During an inspection, the option to enter comments is turned off by default. This way, a teacher is not overloaded with questions and comments from students. A big advantage of turning the option on, however, is that a teacher is then able to download all comments from TestVision.</p>
                <p>Please send an email to <a href="mailto:icto-csw@uva.nl">icto-csw@uva.nl</a> if you'd like to make use of this option.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="element_toggler " aria-controls="FAQ7" aria-label="Toggler toggle list visibility" aria-expanded="false"> <i class="icon-mini-arrow-right"></i><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><a>How do I view all comments on an assignment by a specific student?</a></span> </span></h3>
<ul id="FAQ7" style="list-style: none; display: none;">
    <li>
        <div class="content-box">
            <div style="background-color: #ffffff; padding-left: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #e1e9f4;">
                <p>For inspection, it is important to ask yourself whether an answer model is needed for students. If, for example, you have created an exam with a number of open questions, it is useful for students to see during the inspection how the assessment is done.</p>
                <p>You are completely free to decide what the answer model may look like. The ICTO team asks you to do two things: (1) Please save the answer model in PDF format, and (2) email the PDF file to <a href="mailto:icto-csw@uva.nl">icto-csw@uva.nl</a> at least 3 days before the inspection.</p>
                <p>&nbsp;</p>
                If you have done so, we will make sure the answer model is included in the inspection. This way students can open the answer model on their computer or laptop during the inspection. If it is not convenient for you to deliver the answer model before this deadline, you can still take it with you on USB or print it out for inspection!
                <p>&nbsp;</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </li>
</ul>
